Before starting we need to familiarize with performance terminologies
* Instruction : It tells machine what to do at a given step
* Operation: What a compute unite does to fulfill the instruction
* Clock Cycle: Basic unit to measure instruction time
* Clock speed: Number of clock cycles executed per second.
	- Ex. 1 Ghz = 1 billion cycles per second
* Latency: Delay in processing data after the original instruction
* Throughput : Number of items/instructions processed within a time interval
- Bandwidth: The rate at which data can be transferred.

Q. For a warp how many operations are there in one instruction? 
-> For a warp of size 32, 1 instruction = 32 operations

In order measure number of operations per second we use:
- GFLOPS - 1 billion floating point operations per second
- TFLOPS - 1000 GFLOPS

Since 2003 single core performance has been slowing down due to power and heat limitations but GPU are able do deliver higher FLOP per watt, mm, dollar 

Cache, branch predictor, out of order logic, ALUs are major components of a CPU die. Most of a CPU's die is taken up by cache and controllers.

The usual desktop application's software has serial code but our hardware likes "parallel" code. 

Lets take a loop at a simple CPU core: 

![[Pasted image 20250909134042.png]]

In order to execute any instruction on this CPU following steps need to occur.

Fetch :- Fetching the next instruction to run
Decode :- Taking assembly instruction and decoding it into something that hardware can understand and to decide what instruction to run 
Execute :- Execute the instruction
Memory :- Access the register memory and read or write
Writeback :- Writes the result back to the correct register

This is a single cycle execution. All of these steps occur in one clock period. Here every instruction has to wait for the previous instruction. As a result our CPU remains idle, this is bad utilization.
